  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Once your property is live on the market, your agent should be sending you a weekly campaign report. Most vendors glance at it, see some numbers, and wait for the phone to ring with an offer. That is the wrong approach. The weekly report is the most important feedback loop in your campaign. Reading it correctly tells you whether you are on track for a strong result, and if not, where the problem is.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What should be in every weekly campaign report</h2>
      <p>A complete weekly vendor report covers a consistent set of data points. If your agent is not providing all of these, ask for them.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Total online enquiry count:</strong> The combined number of enquiries from realestate.com.au and domain.com.au for the week. This is the number of people who saw your listing and were interested enough to make contact. It is a measure of how well your marketing is working at the top of the funnel.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Open home attendance:</strong> The number of groups who came through the property in the week's open home or private inspections. This is the conversion from online interest to in-person interest. A large gap between enquiries and inspections is a signal worth investigating.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Cumulative days on market:</strong> The total number of days your property has been listed. In Brisbane's inner east, a well-priced, well-presented property in a healthy market should be generating genuine buyer interest by the end of week two. Beyond four weeks without a contract, questions need to be asked.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Price feedback from buyers:</strong> What inspecting buyers are saying about price, anonymised but specific. Not "mixed feedback" or "buyers are cautious" but actual ranges. "The three groups who came through this week put the property at $1.1m to $1.15m" is useful. "Buyers are uncertain" is not.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Upcoming open home schedule:</strong> When the next open home is scheduled and what the agent plans differently based on this week's performance.</p>

      <p><strong style="color:var(--color-text-primary);">Contract activity:</strong> Whether any verbal offers, written offers, or contract negotiations are in progress. This should include the status of any previous offers and what happened to them.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to read low enquiry numbers</h2>
      <p>In week one and two of a Brisbane campaign, fewer than five enquiries per week is a meaningful warning sign. It suggests one of two things: the price guide is deterring buyers before they even click through, or the marketing is reaching the wrong audience. Neither is a small problem, and both require an immediate conversation with your agent.</p>

      <p>A price guide that is too high filters buyers out at the search stage. Most buyers on realestate.com.au set their search ceiling based on what they can afford. If your price guide sits above that ceiling, they never see your property. A small adjustment to the price guide can dramatically increase the number of buyers seeing the listing, which is the first step to increasing inspections and offers.</p>

      <p>Marketing reach matters too. If the photography is not stopping the scroll, if the listing description is generic, or if the property is not being promoted to the right demographic, enquiries will be low regardless of the price. Your agent should be able to tell you the listing's view-to-enquiry rate from the portal analytics. A high view count but a low enquiry rate suggests the listing itself is the problem.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to read high enquiry but low inspection rate</h2>
      <p>If you are getting strong online enquiry numbers but few people are coming through the property, something is deterring them between clicking on the listing and committing to an inspection. The two most common causes are the price guide and the photos.</p>

      <p>A price guide that creates enthusiasm at the search stage but then disappoints when buyers see comparable sold properties is a classic pattern. Buyers click, they do more research, they decide the guide is aspirational rather than real, and they do not bother inspecting. The fix is to have an honest conversation with your agent about whether the price guide is credible in the current market.</p>

      <p>Poor photography is the other common cause. If the photos do not accurately represent the property's best features, buyers pre-judge it as not worth their Saturday morning. Professional photography that captures the actual quality of the home is one of the highest-return pre-sale investments available to Brisbane sellers.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to read price feedback</h2>
      <p>Price feedback is the most misread section of the weekly report. Agents sometimes soften it to avoid difficult conversations. Sellers sometimes dismiss it because it does not match their expectations. Neither approach helps.</p>

      <p>If buyers are consistently providing price feedback that is 10% to 15% below your reserve or asking price, that is not bad luck and it is not an anomaly. That is the market telling you what the property is worth to the people who have actually walked through it. Three groups of informed buyers, independently providing similar feedback, represent a significant data point. One group's feedback is easy to dismiss. Three is a pattern that needs to be discussed.</p>

      <p>When price feedback clusters consistently below your target, the question to ask your agent is specific: of the buyers who provided that feedback, how many have been through comparable properties that sold recently, and what did those sell for? If the feedback aligns with recent comparable sales, it is accurate. If there is a genuine case that your property is superior to those comparables, your agent should be able to articulate it precisely.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What sellers should ask at the weekly debrief</h2>
      <p>The weekly report should prompt a direct conversation, not just a read-and-acknowledge email exchange. The questions worth asking are specific:</p>

      <p>Which buyers have inspected more than once? Repeat inspectors are the highest-intent buyers in the pool. If none have come back, ask why. If two or three have, those are the people your agent should be calling directly between open homes.</p>

      <p>Which buyers are finance-ready? A buyer who is pre-approved and has a solicitor engaged is qualitatively different from one who is still working out their budget. Your agent should know which of their inspecting buyers fall into each category.</p>

      <p>What is the single biggest objection from inspections this week? Not a summary of everything buyers said, but the one thing that came up most consistently. If four out of six groups mentioned the same concern, that is the issue to address, not to explain away.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a good agent does between open homes</h2>
      <p>The open home is the visible part of the campaign. What happens between open homes is where most of the work is done, and where the quality of your agent shows. A good agent calls every inspecting buyer directly after each open home, before the end of the same day. They ask specific questions: what did you think, what would need to change for you to make an offer, and when would you want to settle? A passive agent sends the portal-generated feedback form and waits for buyers to reply.</p>

      <p>If your weekly report contains no notes about direct buyer follow-up calls, ask your agent what they called each inspecting buyer and what that conversation revealed. If the answer is vague, that is a gap in the campaign that is costing you buyer engagement.</p>

